29d _8301dc9e _115d943f _402af5d4 _8493d9d1 _8180f275 b0ad8e15 _78054f9b f7e6aa03 _2e65307b f507b018 a95c8f86 _40bb1908 _5d7694cd _2ffd07e5 deb4b2ea"><svg/><div class="ce83e726 e3cab0ec _353d12e1"><span class="_2eb95346 _915c7c37 c65f4e21 _900aabf9 b284953a _9a4c5abe e2884f00 _1f780de2 da05719f bf35620b _8377827b _75ec6bde cf86e219 df4fa34d e1496fcf b0bdaf10 _343dfda4 _139eee0f"><span>Follow</span></span></div></span></button></div></div></div></div><p class="_2eb95346 _1f780de2 _74dd6fa4 _2108190c e7d08b7c beb97b95 da5267a2 _39a92184 _0353670a b0ad8e15 aedb061d bec82545 _353d12e1 eacd0d13" componentkey="feed-commentary_ed258c40-31f1-415c-a8e7-86f72fcd66c6"><span class="bed3c864 cf86e219 df4fa34d e1496fcf b0bdaf10 _343dfda4 fbf9de3d ae7bc081" tabindex="-1" data-testid="expandable-text-box">Developers love to overengineer.

Before anyone even uses what we’re building, we’re already thinking about how to scale to millions of users.

We set up CI/CD pipelines, design database schemas, write long architecture docs…

Or at least we used to, now that coding agents handle a lot of that planning and automation.

Building for scale before you have any scale has killed more startups than it’s helped.

Most never even get enough users to need all that.
